FINAL INSIGHTS & RECOMMENDATIONS

Key Insights
•The business generated strong sales (~2.3M) but moderate profit (~286K), indicating low margin efficiency. Growth is driven more by volume than profitability.
•Profit is highly concentrated in a few product categories such as Phones, Copiers, and Chairs, while several sub-categories consistently generate low or negative profit, showing an imbalanced product portfolio.
•High discounts directly reduce profitability, with many loss-making products and transactions linked to aggressive discounting. Sales strategy is currently discount-driven rather than value-driven.
•A significant number of customers are unprofitable, and revenue is concentrated among a limited group of top customers, creating dependency risk and poor customer mix.
•The Consumer segment drives the highest sales, but profitability is not equally strong across all segments, indicating inefficient segment targeting.
•Regionally, West and East perform strongly, while Central and South underperform, with certain states consistently generating losses. This reflects geographical inefficiencies and weak regional strategies.
•Logistics performance shows only ~66% on-time delivery, with a high delay rate (~34%). Most delays originate from Standard Class shipping, indicating a core operational bottleneck.
•Delivery performance shows no consistent improvement trend, and faster delivery does not always result in higher profit, highlighting misalignment between operations and profitability.

Key Recommendations
•Shift to a profit-driven strategy by reducing excessive discounting and implementing strict margin controls across products and transactions.
•Optimize product portfolio by focusing on high-margin categories and eliminating or redesigning consistently loss-making products.
•Improve customer profitability management by identifying high-value customers for retention and limiting discounts or exposure to loss-making customers.
•Strengthen regional strategy by investing in high-performing regions while restructuring or controlling costs in underperforming states.
•Fix logistics inefficiencies, especially in Standard Class shipping, and improve operational processes to increase on-time delivery to at least 85%.
•Align pricing, discounting, and shipping strategies with profitability goals to ensure that business growth translates into actual profit.
•Implement continuous performance monitoring across products, customers, regions, and logistics to support data-driven decision-making.
